// people.ipt
// =====================================================================
// Reusable PF2e NPC generator. Rolls a person: name, ancestry,
// a one-line description, and a personality beat. Designed to be
// imported (Use:) by the shop files so the same person logic backs
// every shopkeeper, worker, and customer.
//
// Entry tables you can call from other files:
//   [@Person]        - full one-line NPC: "Name, a <desc> <ancestry>"
//   [@PersonFull]    - memorable NPC: adds personality + a quirk
//   [@PersonDeep]    - PersonFull plus a motivation/secret hook
//   [@PersonName]    - just a name (ancestry-flavoured mix)
//   [@Ancestry]      - just a PF2e ancestry
//   [@PersonDesc]    - a one-word physical descriptor
//   [@Personality]   - a personality trait phrase
//   [@Quirk]         - a distinctive memorable detail (one sentence)
//   [@Motivation]    - a hidden driver/secret the GM can build on
//   [@PersonCard]    - surface NPC inline + quirk/secret hidden in a
//                      COLLAPSED Obsidian callout (the GM expands it on
//                      demand). The tidy way to keep depth optional.
//   [@PersonCardTitled with <heading>] - PersonCard with a custom
//                      callout heading, e.g. "In the back room".
//
// Depth is opt-in: pick the tier per use. A throwaway NPC uses
// [@Person]; a shopkeeper who should be memorable-but-tidy uses
// [@PersonCard]; a fully-realised NPC uses [@PersonDeep].
//
// PF2e note: ancestries are drawn from the Core Rulebook plus a few
// popular additions (leshy, orc, etc.). Names are deliberately a
// broad fantasy mix rather than strictly per-ancestry naming
// conventions, so any name reads fine with any ancestry. If you want
// strict per-ancestry name lists later, that's a clean extension.

Title: People
Formatting: html

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// Main entry: a complete person in one line.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
Table: Person
{!pname==[@PersonName]}{!panc==[@Ancestry]}{$pname}, a [@PersonDesc] {$panc}

// Just a name. If a prior [@Person]/[@PersonFull]/etc. in the same
// roll already set {pname}, this echoes that same name (so a shop can
// reuse it in a quote). Called standalone — with no {pname} set — it
// rolls a fresh name instead of returning blank.
Table: PersonShort
[when]{$pname}=[do][@PersonName][else]{$pname}[end]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// A fuller, more memorable NPC in one call. Bundles the one-line
// person with a personality beat and a distinctive quirk, so any
// generator can drop in a character that sticks in the memory
// rather than a generic body. Use [@PersonFull] where you want a
// named NPC to actually matter; keep [@Person] for incidental
// mentions.
//   "Sable Voss, a one-eyed dwarf who is dry-humoured and slow to
//    smile. They never sit with their back to a door."
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
Table: PersonFull
{!pname==[@PersonName]}{!panc==[@Ancestry]}{$pname}, a [@PersonDesc] {$panc} who is [@Personality]. [@Quirk]

// Even fuller: adds a motivation/secret hook on the end, for an NPC
// you want to be able to build a thread around.
//   "...They never sit with their back to a door. Quietly, they're
//    saving to buy back a family debt."
Table: PersonDeep
{!pname==[@PersonName]}{!panc==[@Ancestry]}{$pname}, a [@PersonDesc] {$panc} who is [@Personality]. [@Quirk] [@Motivation]

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// Quirk — a distinctive, observable detail that makes an NPC
// memorable: a habit, a tic, a possession, a small mystery. Written
// as a standalone sentence so it drops cleanly onto any description.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
Table: Quirk
They never sit with their back to a door.
They polish a ring that isn't on their finger.
Every sentence somehow circles back to their late spouse.
They count things under their breath when nervous.
A scarred old dog follows them everywhere and trusts no one else.
They collect buttons and will show you the best ones, unprompted.
They speak three languages and mix them mid-sentence.
They flinch at loud noises and pretend they didn't.
They keep a tally of grudges and forget none of them.
They hum an old marching tune without noticing.
They refuse to shake hands, citing reasons that change each time.
They wear far too many rings, each with a story they'll tell.
They never give a straight answer before noon.
They feed the local cats and know each by name.
They carry a child's toy and won't explain it.
They quote scripture they clearly don't believe.
They're missing two fingers and tell a different story each time.
They laugh at the wrong moments, then apologise.
They always know what the weather will do, and they're always right.
They keep glancing at the door as if expecting someone.

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// Motivation — a quiet driver or secret the GM can hang a thread on.
// Phrased so it reads as a hidden truth about the NPC.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
Table: Motivation
Quietly, they're saving to buy back a family debt.
They're hiding from someone who is still looking.
They owe a dangerous person a favour they can't repay.
They're searching for a sibling who vanished years ago.
They're not who they say they are, and never have been.
They'd give anything to leave this town and never can.
They're protecting a secret that would ruin a powerful family.
They believe they're cursed, and they may be right.
They're an informant for someone, willingly or not.
They once did something terrible and have been atoning ever since.
They're in love with someone they absolutely should not be.
They're certain a reckoning is coming, and they're preparing for it.

// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// PersonCard — the surface NPC inline, with the memorable depth
// (quirk + motivation) tucked into a COLLAPSED Obsidian callout that
// the GM expands only when they want it. Keeps a shop's NPC clean at
// a glance while keeping the deeper hooks one click away.
//
// Renders as:
//   **Sable Voss**, a one-eyed dwarf who is dry-humoured and slow to
//   smile.
//   > [!note]- Behind the counter
//   > *Quirk:* They never sit with their back to a door.
//   > *Secret:* They owe a dangerous person a favour they can't repay.
//
// The bracket characters are escaped (\[ \]) so the engine emits them
// literally instead of treating [!note] as a table call. The blank
// line before the callout (via \n\n) separates it from the inline
// description so Obsidian renders the callout block correctly.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
Table: PersonCard
{!pname==[@PersonName]}{!panc==[@Ancestry]}**{$pname}**, a [@PersonDesc] {$panc} who is [@Personality].\n&
\n&
> \[!note\]- Behind the counter\n&
> *Quirk:* [@Quirk]\n&
> *Secret:* [@Motivation]

// Variant with a caller-supplied callout heading, so a location can
// label it appropriately ("Behind the bar", "In the back room", etc.).
// Pass the heading as the parameter: [@PersonCardTitled with In the vestry]
Table: PersonCardTitled
{!pname==[@PersonName]}{!panc==[@Ancestry]}**{$pname}**, a [@PersonDesc] {$panc} who is [@Personality].\n&
\n&
> \[!note\]- {$1}\n&
> *Quirk:* [@Quirk]\n&
> *Secret:* [@Motivation]


